  <static seed="1306" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions6.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{2+\frac{1}{q-3}}}{{\frac{1}{q-3}-\frac{1}{3}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{3\mathopen{}\left(2q-5\right)}{-q+6}, q\ne 3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{2+\frac{1}{q-3}}}{{\frac{1}{q-3}-\frac{1}{3}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{2+\frac{1}{q-3}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{q-3}-\frac{1}{3}}</m>, which is <m>{3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{2+\frac{1}{q-3}}}{{\frac{1}{q-3}-\frac{1}{3}}} \amp = \frac{({2+\frac{1}{q-3}})\cdot{3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)}}{({\frac{1}{q-3}-\frac{1}{3}})\cdot{3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{2\cdot 3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)+\frac{1}{q-3}\cdot 3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)}}{{\frac{1}{q-3}\cdot 3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)-\frac{1}{3}\cdot 3\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{6\mathopen{}\left(q-3\right)+3}}{{3-\left(q-3\right)}} , q\ne3 \\
    \amp = \frac{{6q-18+3}}{{3-q+3}}, q\ne3  \\
    \amp = \frac{{6q-15}}{{6-q}}, q\ne3 \\
    \amp = {\frac{3\mathopen{}\left(2q-5\right)}{-q+6}, q\ne 3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>q-3</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>q \ne 3</m>.</p>
</solution>
